```

### 2. Interior Mutability Approach
Use RefCell or similar for relationship fields:
```rust
pub struct Related<T: Model> {
    fk_value: Option<Value>,
    loaded: RefCell<Option<T>>,  // Interior mutability
}

pub struct RelatedMany<T: Model> {
    parent_pk: Option<Value>,
    loaded: RefCell<Vec<T>>,     // Interior mutability
}

// Now we can modify even through shared references
impl<T: Model> RelatedMany<T> {
    pub fn push(&self, item: T) {
        self.loaded.borrow_mut().push(item);
    }

    pub fn remove_by_pk(&self, pk: &Value) {
        self.loaded.borrow_mut().retain(|i| i.pk() != pk);
    }
}
```

### 3. Session-Aware Approach (Preferred)
Better: Do sync through Session, which tracks all objects:
```rust
impl Session {
    /// Set a relationship with automatic back_populates sync.
    pub fn relate<L: Model, R: Model>(&self, left: &L, right: &R) -> Result<()> {
        // Look up relationship info
        let rel = L::relationship_to::<R>()?;

        // Update left side
        // left.{relationship_field} = Related::loaded(right.clone())

        // If back_populates defined, update right side
        if let Some(back) = rel.back_populates {
            // right.{back_field}.push(left.clone()) or .set(left)
        }

        // Mark both as dirty
        self.mark_dirty(left)?;
        self.mark_dirty(right)?;

        Ok(())
    }
}

// Usage:
session.relate(&hero, &team)?;
// Both hero.team and team.heroes are now in sync
```

### 4. Validation: Verify back_populates Symmetry
At compile time or runtime, verify that back_populates references exist and are consistent:
```rust
// In the macro or at runtime init
fn validate_back_populates<M: Model>() {
    for rel in M::RELATIONSHIPS {
        if let Some(back) = rel.back_populates {
            // The related model must have a relationship pointing back
            let back_rel = related_model.relationship_by_name(back);
            assert!(back_rel.is_some(), "back_populates points to non-existent relationship");
            assert_eq!(back_rel.related_table, M::table_name(), "back_populates mismatch");
        }
    }
}
```

## Design Decision: When Does Sync Happen?

Option A: **Immediate Sync** (SQLAlchemy style)
- Setting hero.team immediately updates team.heroes
- Requires interior mutability or Session tracking
- Can be surprising if objects aren't in same Session

Option B: **Deferred Sync** (Session.flush style)
- Changes queued until flush()
- Session reconciles all relationships at flush time
- More predictable, works better with Rust ownership

**Recommendation**: Option B (deferred sync) is more Rust-idiomatic.

